You are writing the VIEW/API layer. Routes are thin — they receive, validate, delegate, and respond.

## Route rules
- Routes call controllers ONLY — never import or call agents directly
- Every route must be async
- Return 202 + job_id for any operation taking >2s (use background tasks + polling)
- Return 200 for sync responses, 422 for validation errors (FastAPI handles automatically)
- Every endpoint needs a `response_model=` and `summary=` for OpenAPI docs

## Response schema rules
- All response schemas extend `BaseResponseSchema` from `backend/api/schemas/base.py`
- Never import from agents/ or tools/ — only from domain/ and controllers/
- Every `Field()` must have `example=` for automatic OpenAPI documentation
- Response schemas are READ-ONLY projections of domain models — use `model_validate()`

## Forbidden in api/
- No business logic whatsoever
- No direct LLM calls
- No raw dict returns — always a typed response schema
- No blocking I/O in route handlers
